* Task 1 for AI 
  Here is your task. I want to be able to run a docker compose file that will run a local server that can preform hot reloading. 
  Right now, this is combersome as air right now does hot reload, but there is no way for me to debug using delve and neovim with it. 
  feel free to leverage Makefiles to accomplish this task.
  I should need only to run the make target and a launch.json. 
  All the files you need are in the {* Links} section below
** Deliverables
  - the mindscape web server running on port 60000
  - the development config being used for the configuration of the server
  - the hot reloading of the server when the code changes 
  - the hot reloading of the frontend when the code changes
** Steps
   - Make a plan for how you will do this.
   - Add a section in this document for each step.
   - viwe the links below for reference of which files i want you to use
   - when you are done write out a summary of what you did here in a {* Report}
	 with also a full outline of what i need to do in order to complete the debugging process.

** Implementation Sections

*** Step 1: Created Development Dockerfile (dev.Dockerfile)
    Created a new Dockerfile specifically for development that includes:
    - Golang 1.24 base image with all necessary tools
    - Air for hot reloading backend code
    - Delve (dlv) for debugging support
    - Node.js and pnpm for frontend development
    - All required tools: git, make, curl, ffmpeg
    - Exposes three ports: 60000 (app), 2345 (debugger), 5173 (frontend)
    - Mounts source code as volumes for instant hot reloading
    - Startup script that runs both frontend dev server and backend with air

*** Step 2: Created Debug Air Configuration (.air.debug.toml)
    Created a specialized Air configuration that:
    - Compiles Go code with debug symbols (-gcflags='all=-N -l')
    - Runs the binary through Delve in headless mode
    - Listens on port 2345 for remote debugging connections
    - Supports multi-client connections (allows reconnecting)
    - Watches Go files for changes and rebuilds automatically
    - Excludes test files and frontend directories from watch

*** Step 3: Created Development Docker Compose (dev.docker-compose.yml)
    Created a new docker-compose configuration that:
    - Uses the dev.Dockerfile for building
    - Exposes all three required ports
    - Mounts source code as volumes for hot reloading
    - Excludes node_modules and tmp directories from mounts
    - Passes all environment variables from .env file
    - Adds SYS_PTRACE capability for Delve debugging
    - Includes health checks for the application
    - Overrides command to use .air.debug.toml configuration

*** Step 4: Added Makefile Targets
    Added four new Makefile targets for Docker development workflow:
    - `make dev-docker`: Starts the development Docker environment with build
    - `make dev-docker-down`: Stops and removes the development containers
    - `make dev-docker-logs`: Follows the logs of the development container
    - `make dev-docker-rebuild`: Force rebuilds and recreates the containers

    Each target includes helpful colored output showing available URLs and ports.

*** Step 5: Updated launch.json
    Added a new debugging configuration:
    - Name: "Attach to Docker Delve"
    - Connects to localhost:2345 (Delve server in container)
    - Maps container path /app to local workspace
    - Enables verbose logging for debugging the debugger
    - Works with VS Code and Neovim DAP (nvim-dap)

* Report

** Summary
   Successfully implemented a complete Docker-based development environment for Mindscape using a
   two-container architecture that provides:
   - Separate containers for frontend and backend (clean log separation)
   - Hot reloading for both backend (Air) and frontend (pnpm dev)
   - Full debugging support via Delve debugger
   - Single command startup with `make dev-docker`
   - Individual service control and log viewing
   - Proper container networking for frontend-backend communication
   - Development config usage (development.yaml)
   - All services running on specified ports

** Architecture Overview
   The solution uses a *microservices-style two-container architecture*:

   *Container 1: Backend (mindscape-backend)*
   - Go application with Air for hot reloading
   - Delve debugger for breakpoint debugging
   - Exposes ports 60000 (API) and 2345 (debugger)
   - Mounts Go source code for hot reload

   *Container 2: Frontend (mindscape-frontend)*
   - Node.js with pnpm dev server
   - SolidJS application with hot module replacement
   - Exposes port 5173 (dev server)
   - Mounts web/ directory for hot reload
   - Proxies API requests to backend container

   *Container Communication*
   - Custom Docker bridge network: `mindscape-network`
   - Frontend reaches backend at `http://backend:60000` via DNS
   - Rsbuild proxy configuration uses BACKEND_URL environment variable

   The solution consists of six key components:

   1. *Backend Dockerfile (dev.Dockerfile)* - Backend with Air + Delve
   2. *Frontend Dockerfile (web.Dockerfile)* - Frontend with pnpm dev server
   3. *Debug Air Config (.air.debug.toml)* - Configures Air to run through Delve
   4. *Dev Docker Compose (dev.docker-compose.yml)* - Orchestrates both containers with networking
   5. *Makefile Targets* - Convenient commands for managing both services
   6. *Launch Configuration (.vscode/launch.json)* - Enables remote debugging from Neovim/VS Code

** Complete Debugging Process Guide

*** Initial Setup (One-time)
    1. Ensure you have Docker and Docker Compose installed
    2. Ensure you have a `.env` file with all required EGG_* environment variables
    3. Ensure you have Neovim with nvim-dap configured for Go debugging
       - Or VS Code with the Go extension installed

*** Starting the Development Environment
    1. Open a terminal in the mindscape project root
    2. Run: `make dev-docker`
    3. Wait for both containers to build and start (first time takes longer)
    4. You should see output indicating:
       - Backend container (mindscape-backend) building and starting
       - Frontend container (mindscape-frontend) building and starting
       - Backend API on port 60000
       - Frontend dev server on port 5173
       - Delve debugger listening on port 2345
    5. In separate terminals, view individual logs:
       - Backend: `make dev-docker-logs-backend` (shows Air + Delve output)
       - Frontend: `make dev-docker-logs-frontend` (shows pnpm dev output)
    6. Verify services are running:
       - Backend: http://localhost:60000/api/_health
       - Frontend: http://localhost:5173
       - Check containers: `docker ps | grep mindscape`

*** Debugging with Neovim
    1. Ensure the dev-docker containers are running (see above)
    2. Open Neovim in the mindscape project directory
    3. Open the file you want to debug (e.g., main.go or any handler)
    4. Set breakpoints using your DAP plugin:
       - For nvim-dap: `:lua require('dap').toggle_breakpoint()`
       - Or use your keybinding (commonly `<leader>db`)
    5. Start debugging by attaching to the remote debugger:
       - Use the "Attach to Docker Delve" configuration
       - In nvim-dap: `:lua require('dap').continue()`
       - Or use your keybinding (commonly `<F5>`)
    6. The debugger will connect to port 2345 and pause at your breakpoints
    7. Use standard DAP commands to step through code:
       - Step Over: `<F10>` or `:lua require('dap').step_over()`
       - Step Into: `<F11>` or `:lua require('dap').step_into()`
       - Continue: `<F5>` or `:lua require('dap').continue()`

*** Debugging with VS Code
    1. Ensure the dev-docker containers are running
    2. Open VS Code in the mindscape project directory
    3. Open the file you want to debug
    4. Set breakpoints by clicking in the gutter next to line numbers
    5. Open the Run and Debug panel (Ctrl+Shift+D)
    6. Select "Attach to Docker Delve" from the dropdown
    7. Click the green play button or press F5
    8. The debugger will attach and pause at your breakpoints
    9. Use the debugging toolbar to step through code

*** Hot Reloading Behavior
    - *Backend*: When you save any .go file:
      - Air detects the change
      - Rebuilds the binary with debug symbols
      - Restarts Delve with the new binary
      - Your debugger may disconnect briefly and need to reconnect
      - Set breakpoints again after reload

    - *Frontend*: When you save any .tsx, .ts, or .css file:
      - pnpm dev detects the change
      - Hot-reloads the module in the browser
      - No debugger impact
      - Browser updates automatically

*** Stopping the Environment
    1. To stop the containers: `make dev-docker-down`
    2. Or press Ctrl+C in the terminal running `make dev-docker`
    3. This stops and removes the containers but preserves volumes

*** Troubleshooting
    - *Debugger won't connect*:
      - Check that port 2345 is exposed: `docker ps`
      - Check Delve is running: `make dev-docker-logs-backend`
      - Ensure no other service is using port 2345
      - Verify backend container is running: `docker ps | grep backend`

    - *Backend hot reload not working*:
      - Verify volumes are mounted: `docker inspect mindscape-backend`
      - Check Air logs: `make dev-docker-logs-backend`
      - Try rebuilding backend: `make dev-docker-rebuild`

    - *Frontend hot reload not working*:
      - Verify web directory is mounted: `docker inspect mindscape-frontend`
      - Check frontend logs: `make dev-docker-logs-frontend`
      - Restart frontend: `make dev-docker-restart-frontend`

    - *Frontend can't reach backend*:
      - Check both containers are on same network: `docker network inspect mindscape-network`
      - Verify BACKEND_URL is set: `make dev-docker-logs-frontend`
      - Check backend health: `curl http://localhost:60000/api/_health`

    - *Container won't start*:
      - Check environment variables are set in .env
      - Verify database/Redis/MinIO are accessible
      - Check logs: `make dev-docker-logs-backend` or `make dev-docker-logs-frontend`
      - Rebuild from scratch: `make dev-docker-rebuild`

*** Additional Commands
    *Viewing Logs*
    - View all logs: `make dev-docker-logs`
    - View backend logs only: `make dev-docker-logs-backend`
    - View frontend logs only: `make dev-docker-logs-frontend`

    *Restarting Services*
    - Restart backend only: `make dev-docker-restart-backend`
    - Restart frontend only: `make dev-docker-restart-frontend`
    - Rebuild everything: `make dev-docker-rebuild`

    *Container Access*
    - Access backend shell: `docker exec -it mindscape-backend sh`
    - Access frontend shell: `docker exec -it mindscape-frontend sh`
    - Check container status: `docker ps | grep mindscape`

** Benefits of This Solution
   - *Clean Separation*: Frontend and backend in separate containers with isolated logs
   - *Easy Debugging*: View backend or frontend logs independently
   - *Single Command Startup*: `make dev-docker` starts both containers
   - *Individual Service Control*: Restart backend or frontend independently
   - *Hot Reloading*: Both services automatically reload on file changes
   - *Full Debugging Support*: Delve debugger with breakpoints and stepping
   - *Complete Isolation*: No conflicts with local Go or Node installations
   - *Production-like Architecture*: Microservices setup mirrors real deployment
   - *Consistent Environment*: Same setup across all developer machines
   - *Easy to Reset*: Rebuild individual or all containers as needed
   - *Port Conflict Free*: Can run multiple projects simultaneously

** Files Modified/Created
   - Created: `dev.Dockerfile` (backend development container)
   - Created: `web.Dockerfile` (frontend development container)
   - Created: `.air.debug.toml` (Air config for Delve debugging)
   - Created: `dev.docker-compose.yml` (orchestrates both containers)
   - Modified: `Makefile` (added dev-docker targets for both services)
   - Modified: `.vscode/launch.json` (added remote debug config)
   - Modified: `web/rsbuild.config.ts` (added BACKEND_URL environment variable support)
